EDA_Project

Candidate Contributions by Alejandro Garcia

The following dataset is about the Financial contributions that took place for the state of Texas during the 2016 election year. It contains data on minor information on the contributors and the amounts they contributed to the candidates as well as candidate names, commitee ids, and candidate ids.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The current structure of my dataset consist of 548,396 observations and 21 variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

I am interested in finding the amount of contributions made to those candidates running for the 2016 presidential elections in the state of TX.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

cand_nam, contbr_nm, contb_receipt_amt, cont_day,month, and contb_amt.bracket

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I had to create the cont_day, cont_month_, and cont_year which replaced the contbr_receipt_dt. The contb_amt.bracket was also created to help reduce the amount of bins needed to capture all of the dollar amounts contributed.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Of the features I investigated, I did not notice any unusual distributions. But I did notice that contbr_zip and contbr_city were not usable since some zip codesand cities were made up or other countries.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

In this section I wanted to look at the amount of money a candadite received everyday for the two or three years where contributors donated money. I also focused on the combined number of contributions in a month.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

In this section I decided to create a new set of data that contained the contribution amounts each candidated received and the amount of contributors. Althought Hillary Clintion did not win the election she had the highest amount of contributors with 203K and the highest contribution amount of $22.6 million.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Unfortuntaly I was unable to perform a cor test to find any strong correlations between the data my dataset contained. The majority of my data is factor based and numerical values are needed to perform a cor test.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

The contribution amounts began in 2013 with contribution amount picking up in 2015 and amounts sky rocketing in 2016. We observed that there were quite a few contributors in 2015 with the contributions picking up in November and December. After the elections were over, a few contributors continued to contribute until late December 2016, over a month since the elections ended, thats also where we can observe the majority of the contributions over $2001 occurring.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

95% of the contribution amounts were under $500 dollars which equate to $26,654,520. As mentioned above during the month of December of 2016 $76994.23 was contributed to the campains.

Plot One

Description One

Here we take a look at the contribution amounts by brackets. 95% of the contribution amounts were under $500. There were over 80,000 contributions of $25 made with the next highest contribution amount being $50 with a count of 69,794.

Plot Two

Description Two

This shows us a greater picture showing the total amount of money contributed per day, by month, and year. We can largly see that 2016 had the highest number of monetary contributions followed by 2015. The amounts donated during 2013 and 2014 are almost nonexistent on this chart.

Plot Three

Description Three

This shows the total number of contributions made on each day in a four year period and colored by month. Each color block represents the number of contributions made on that day.

Reflection

So this was a pretting interesting data set to work with. It contained the presidential election contribution information on the candidates and those who contributed to the campaigns. The dataset was based on the contributions from the great state of Texas. Although the state of Texas itself is a mostly Republican state there was quite a surprise when I found that a Democrat won out on the number of contributions made and the total amount of contributions made. I did have a bit of trouble with the dataset itself though, it was mostly comprived of strings and factors unlike the daimonds dataset which makes it easier to work with since it has a ton of numeric based data. The main variables used were cand_nm, contb_nm, contb_receipt_amt, cont_day, cont_month,cont_year, and contb_amt.bracket. If I were to work with this dataset again in the future I might try and divide candidates into their respective political groups.
